```typescript
import { test as base } from '@playwright/test';
import { allure } from 'allure-playwright';

const modifyLabels = [
  async ({ }, use, testInfo) => {
    allure.layer('system');
    await use();
  },
  { auto: true },
]

const test = base.extend({
  modifyLabels,
});

test.skip('foo', () => {
  // this test isn't at system layer, because it's skipped
});

test('bar', () => {
  test.skip();
  // this test is at system layer, but developers don't write it this way
});

base('baz', () => {
  // this test is in the same file, but uses different test function
  // if you set all tests to system layer in reporter proxy, it has to go in a different file and different PW config
});
```

In general there is no way to reliably annotate tests if they are skipped.

What I propose is

```typescript
const modifyLabels = [
  async ({ }, use, testInfo) => {
    allure.layer('system');
    await use();
  },
  { always: true },
]

test.skip('foo', () => {
  // fixture was executed, body of the test wasn't
});
```

@dgozman @pavelfeldman This issue might have been accidentally closed. Linked solution doesn't solve the problem.

If we were to use annotations instead of fixtures here, it'd take several extra lines of code _per every test in repository_.

I don't see how that might make the code any more readable compared to calling `test.skip();`.

Hey @dgozman , @pavelfeldman , we would exactly have the same use case as described by @throw5way. We currently have all teams specify the test metadata like author, ticket, app, etc. in the test.use block, and then have an auto-test fixture to read those properties, verify them, and set them as annotations to pass to our custom reporters. 

Sadly, this does not work for skipped tests. As discussed above, the auto fixture body will not get executed, and therefore, we are missing all the metadata information for skipped tests, which is not really good. 

The perfect solution for us would be exactly what @throw5way described [here](https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/issues/29229#issuecomment-1921221023). So, to have a fixture option "always" that gets executed no matter the test resolution. Copy of the proposed solution:
```ts
const modifyLabels = [
  async ({ }, use, testInfo) => {
    allure.layer('system');
    await use();
  },
  { always: true },
]

test.skip('foo', () => {
  // fixture was executed, body of the test wasn't
}); 
```

issue.body:
###  Feature Request

Originates from: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/issues/29229

We currently have all teams specify metadata information such as author, ticket, app, tags in the `test.use({...})` block, in the following way:
```typescript
test.use({
  author: Author.SOME_AUTHOR,
  ticket: 'TICKET-1234',
  app: APPS.SOME_APP,
  tags: ['some-tag'],
});
```

This has the great benefit, that it is not needed to specify the information for each test, in case it is the same, because it re-uses the information for each test in the same file, until a new `test.use` block is specified. 

Sadly, we have the issue with this implementation that skipped tests are not reported because the auto test-scoped fixture, in which we pick up, validate, and send the metadata to our custom reporters, is not executed. 

how our auto test-scoped fixture looks like:
```typescript
  metaDataHandler: [
    async ({ page, app, author, ticket, tags, userRole, logger, browser }, use, testInfo) => {

      // do some validation & attach it to the metadata.json via `testInfo.attach(...`
      await use(); // execute test
    },
    { auto: true, scope: 'test' },
  ],
```

Therefore, I would like to request a new fixture option that allows running the fixture no matter the test result. Thanks already in advance for your efforts!

### Example

### Usage:
```typescript
import { test as base } from '@playwright/test';

type CustomFixtures = {
  metaDataHandler: void;
};
type CustomOptions = {
  author: string;
};

const test = base.extend<CustomOptions & CustomFixtures>({
  author: undefined,
  metaDataHandler: [
    async ({ author }, use, testInfo) => {
      if (!author) {
        throw Error('Please specify an author for the test');
      }
      console.info(`Test Author: ${author}`);
      await testInfo.attach('metadata.json', { body: JSON.stringify({ author: author }) });
      await use();
    },
    { scope: 'test', auto: true, always: true }, // <- new option "always: true" which means that it will always executed no matter if the test was skipped or not
  ],
});

test.use({ author: 'max.mustermann' });

test('tryout', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://playwright.dev/docs');
  // Expected output: Test Author: max.mustermann
});

test.skip('skiped tryout', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://playwright.dev/docs');
  // Expected output: Test Author: max.mustermann
});

```





### Motivation

Especially in bigger companies with platform products, where teams have their own repositories for their app, it is important to have insights into the health/maturity of the app in order to instrument the correct quality gates that prevent or allow a new release of the app in production.

One thing that is important for such a quality gate, is to have an overview of all the tests in a central place that shows what features/pages are tested in a certain version of the app or, even more importantly, what features are not tested for that app because the tests are skipped (or no tests exist at all) and could potentially cause an app failure in production.

Therefore, it is important to also send the metadata information for skipped tests to ensure that the people responsible for new app releases are aware.
